</figure>

### 2. Copy Books by Hand

Pick a favorite book, a pen, and some paper. Copy a few paragraphs each day. It''s a calming way to practice focus and slip into a flow state.

<figure>
<img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517971129774-8a2b38fa128e?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w3Mjc2NjN8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwyfHxyZWFkaW5nJTIwYm9vayUyMGhhbmR3cml0aW5nJTIwc3R1ZHl8ZW58MHx8fHwxNzQyOTc2MDE3fDA&ixlib=rb-4.0.3&q=80&w=2000" alt="Person writing in a journal" style="width:100%; max-height:600px; object-fit:cover;">
<figcaption>Hand-copying text engages multiple brain regions, improving both concentration and information retention.</figcaption>
</figure>

### 3. Retell What You Read

Read a short passage, close the book, and recount it in detail. Begin with simple stories and aim for accuracy. This sharpens both focus and memory.

## Extra Tips to Stay on Track

Try these bonus tricks to keep distractions at bay:

- **Pomodoro Technique**: Work for 25 minutes, then break for 5. It keeps you fresh and focused.
- **Mindfulness Moments**: Spend 10 minutes breathing deeply. It trains your brain to ignore noise.
- **One Task at a Time**: Multitasking kills focusâ€”stick to one thing until it''s done.
- **Clear Your Space**: Silence notifications and tidy up. A clean setup boosts concentration.
- **Rest and Recharge**: Fix your sleep and eat well. A healthy body fuels a focused mind.

